LAGOS  – Manufacturers Association of Nigeria (MAN) has stated that the manufacturing production value in Nigeria declined to N2.36 trillion in the second half of 2020 from N7.38 trillion recorded in the corresponding half of 2019. MAN stated this in its Executive Summary Bi-Annual Review of the Economy released to the media. According to MAN, the N2.36 trillion declines indicated N5.02 trillion reductions over July – December 2020. HOW NIGERIAN MEN CAN NOW NATURALLY STOP PREMATURE EJACULATION, LOW SPERM COUNT AND OTHER MEN'S SEXUAL NEEDS. MADAM ALWAYS WANTS IT BIGGER, STRONGER AND LONG-LASTING!!! MAN, however, said that manufacturing production for the period under review increased by N0.32 trillion or 15.5 per cent when compared with N2.04 trillion recorded in the first half of 2020. The report emphasised that production value in the sector totalled N4.4 trillion in 2020 as against N11.99 trillion achieved in 2019, stressing that the uptick in the second half over the performance in the first half of the year was due to the opening up of the economy for businesses after over five months of lockdown to contain the spread of COVID-19 pandemic. FG To Partner KACCIMA On Kano Trade Fair Complex Rehabilitation COVID-19: CACOVID Donates Incinerator, 260 Oxygen Cylinders To Lagos Besides, the report stated that manufacturing capacity utilisation edged up to 53.7 per cent in the second half of 2020 from 43.2 per cent recorded in the first half of the year, thereby, indicating 8.5 percentage point increase over the period. But, pointed out that such declined by 5.74 per cent when compared with 59.44 per cent recorded in the corresponding half of 2019. “Capacity utilisation in the sector averaged 49.5 per cent in 2020 as against 56.8 per cent recorded in 2019. The uptick in capacity utilisation in the period is attributed to the relaxing of the COVID-19 containment measures, particularly the opening of the economy for business activities in the second half 2020. “The increase is also seasonally influenced as a result of Christmas celebration boosted economic activities in the last quarter of the year,” it said. Globally, it said in the third quarter of 2020, global manufacturing output declined by 1.1 per cent in a year-over-year comparison due to COVID-19 containment measures, following a significant drop of 11.1 per cent in the second quarter of 2020. It lamented that the COVID-19 pandemic that began in Wuhan, China, spread across the world, decapitating global economies as evident in the record death toll of manpower; the crashing of crude oil price, the slowed global supply and demand and the total halting of economic activities at the highpoint of the period.